04860nam a22008775i 9783110482324DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20162016gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)958052212  a97831104823247 a10.1515/97831104823242doi  a(DE-B1597)466961  a(OCoLC)954046804  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aPA3084.P7bS57 2016 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04a881.01223  aFE 4451qBVB2rvk0(DE-625)rvk/30313:1 aSistakou, Evina, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTragic Failures :bAlexandrian Responses to Tragedy and the Tragic /cEvina Sistakou. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2016] 4c©2016  a1 online resource (XII, 249 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aTrends in Classics - Supplementary Volumes ,x1868-4785 ;v3800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tPreface -- tIntroduction: From Tragedy to the Tragic -- t1. Tragedy, from Athens to Alexandria -- t2. The Metaclassical Tragic -- t3. Alexandrian Tragedy -- t4. Callimachus Displaces the Tragic -- t5. Redefining the Tragic in the Idylls of Theocritus -- t6. Tragedy into Epic in Apollonius’ Argonautica -- t7. In the Metatragic Cosmos of the Alexandra -- t8. The Romantic Tragic -- tConclusion: Tragic Failures and Hellenistic Challenges -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the first study considering the reception of Greek tragedy and the transformation of the tragic idea in Hellenistic poetry. The focus is on third-century Alexandria, where the Ptolemies fostered tragedy as a theatrical form for public entertainment and as an official genre cultivated by the Pleiad, whereas the scholars of the Museum were commissioned to edit and comment on the classical tragic texts. More importantly, the notion of the tragic was adapted to the literary trends of the era. Released from the strict rules established by Aristotle about what makes a good tragedy, the major poets of the Alexandrian avant-garde struggled to transform the tragic idea and integrate it into non-dramatic genres. Tragic Failures traces the incorporation of the tragic idea in the poetry of Callimachus and Theocritus, in Apollonius’ epic Argonautica, in the iambic Alexandra, in late Hellenistic poetry and in Parthenius’ Erotika Pathemata. It offers a fascinating insight into the new conception of the tragic dilemmas in the context of Alexandrian aesthetics.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aGreek poetry, HellenisticxHistory and criticism. 4aAlexandrinische Ästhetik. 4aHellenistische Dichtung. 4aTragödie. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAlexandrian aesthetics.  aHellenistic poetry.  atragedy.  atragic.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus DeG Package 2016 Part 1z978311076250108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG Plus eBook-Package 2016z978311070100508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2016z9783110485103oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Classical Studies 2016z9783110485097oZDB-23-DGD0 cEPUBz97831104806340 cprintz978311047912640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978311048232440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9783110482324423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9783110482324/original  a978-3-11-070100-5  DG Plus eBook-Package 2016b2016  a978-3-11-076250-1  DG Plus DeG Package 2016 Part 1b2016  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_DGALL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK  aZDB-23-DGDb2016  aZDB-23-DGGb2016